<section class="card">
  <h2>About Zucchini</h2>

  <p class="tagline">
    Fast warm-season producer—moderate heat demand, no frost tolerance.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Zucchini is frost-tender and can be killed at 32°F (0°C).</strong>
    In a typical year (1991–2020 climate normals at the 50% probability level), zucchini viability depends on planting after last frost, accumulating sufficient Growing Degree Days (GDD), and producing before first fall frost.
  </p>

  <p>
    Compared to winter squash, zucchini matures quickly and requires less total heat.
    In short seasons, it is often one of the more reliable warm-season crops if planted into warm soil.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Planning Reference</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Direct sow:</strong> 2–4 weeks after last frost (soil consistently warm)</li>
    <li><strong>Indoor start (optional):</strong> 2–3 weeks before transplant window</li>
    <li><strong>Days to maturity:</strong> 45–60 days</li>
    <li><strong>Frost tolerance:</strong> None (killed at 32°F / 0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted">
    These are baseline ranges. Early planting into cool soil reduces growth speed and shrinks risk margin.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Temperature & Soil Requirements</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Minimum soil temperature:</strong> ~60°F (16°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Optimal growth:</strong> 70–90°F (21–32°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Slow growth:</strong> Below ~60°F (16°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Freeze damage:</strong> 32°F (0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Zucchini stalls in cool soil and cool nights.
    Waiting for warm soil before planting preserves development speed and increases harvest runway before first frost.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    For frost probability framing, see:
    <a href="/guides/average-frost-date-vs-actual-weather/">Average frost date vs actual weather</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Requirement</h2>

  <p><strong>Base temperature:</strong> 50°F (10°C)</p>
  <p><strong>Approximate GDD needed:</strong> ~900–1,200 GDD (base 50)</p>

  <p>
    Zucchini is moderately heat-dependent. It requires fewer accumulated GDD than winter squash but still depends on steady summer heat to maintain production.
  </p>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
  </div>

  <p class="fine">
    For the combined frost + heat framework, see:
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How frost dates and Growing Degree Days work together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Minimum Frost-Free Days</h2>

  <p>
    Most zucchini varieties begin harvest in <strong>45–60 frost-free days</strong>.
    Continued harvest depends on sustained warmth and plant health.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Check Your Frost-Free Season</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Viability Flag</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Good choice under 100 days?</strong> Yes (reliable warm-season option)</li>
    <li><strong>Risky under 90 days?</strong> Occasionally, if spring soil warms slowly</li>
    <li><strong>Needs season extension?</strong> Sometimes helpful early (black mulch or row cover for warmth)</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>First Frost Sensitivity</h2>

  <p>
    Zucchini has no frost tolerance buffer. A freeze at 32°F (0°C) ends production immediately.
    First frost is therefore a hard seasonal boundary.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Early-Maturing Strategy</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Wait for warm soil before planting</li>
    <li>Select compact or early varieties in tight frost windows</li>
    <li>Use full sun exposure to maximize effective heat accumulation</li>
    <li>Plant in heat-retaining microclimates when possible</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Model</h2>

  <p class="muted">
    Frost → Season Length → GDD → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin
  </p>

  <p>
    In a typical year, zucchini is viable when your frost-free window and seasonal heat budget exceed the crop’s modest maturity requirement.
    Early-season cold is the most common way risk margin is reduced.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>Can zucchini survive frost?</h3>
  <p>
    No. Zucchini is frost-sensitive and can be damaged or killed at 32°F (0°C).
  </p>

  <h3>Is zucchini easier than winter squash in short seasons?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. Zucchini typically requires fewer frost-free days and less accumulated heat than most winter squash types.
  </p>

  <h3>Why did my zucchini grow slowly early in the season?</h3>
  <p>
    Cool soil and cool nights commonly slow early growth, reducing development speed and maturity buffer.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Use 32°F (0°C) as the frost boundary (50% probability, 1991–2020 normals).</li>
    <li>Zucchini is frost-sensitive but moderately heat-demanding.</li>
    <li>Typical requirement: 45–60 days, ~900–1,200 GDD (base 50).</li>
    <li>Model viability using frost window + seasonal heat budget + variety requirement + risk margin.</li>
  </ul>
</section>